WEBVTT

00:02.579 --> 00:13.072
I

00:02.579 --> 00:13.072
guess it was 16 years ago.

00:14.533 --> 00:18.258
He wanted me to meet George Mitchell. So I met 
George Mitchell, and at that time, he had become

00:18.278 --> 00:28.009
very much involved in the issue of sustainable 
societies and limits to growth. And so I got

00:28.971 --> 00:31.033
involved with the Club of Rome. and decided he 
would commit himself to these five biannual

00:32.313 --> 00:38.280
conferences, international conferences 
dealing with the issue. At that time, he called it

00:38.320 --> 00:40.343
Limits to Growth. And I knew absolutely nothing 
about that and cared less. I thought it was

00:45.208 --> 00:53.438
futurism and I wasn't going to get involved in 
that, but President Hoffman persuaded me

00:45.208 --> 00:53.438
otherwise. And I'm delighted he did. Anyway, as a 
result of that first interaction, over the last,

01:01.186 --> 01:12.081
ever since then, there's just been a series of 
activities and projects that I've gotten, I've

01:01.186 --> 01:12.081
been involved with George Mitchell. To finally 
about, I don't know, maybe six years ago, in the

01:12.662 --> 01:29.826
early stages of HARC,

01:12.662 --> 01:29.826
he asked me to serve as interim director of HARC, 
interim president. And during the next few

01:30.346 --> 01:37.697
months, the search began for a president, and Skip 
Porter was recruited. And when I was done with

01:38.779 --> 01:45.228
that, he asked me to do something else related to 
his dream of having a campus out here. He had this

01:45.248 --> 01:50.897
gift on the table at the University of Houston for 
all these years, and then he had to come with it. And

01:52.519 --> 01:55.864
that was followed by something related to the 
research for us and finally he and I talked and I

01:57.397 --> 02:07.832
said that I think I was ready for the switch. I just 
wanted to do something different. I thought this

02:11.477 --> 02:15.964
was a wonderful opportunity to enter the private 
sector and really earn some big money. My timing

02:17.045 --> 02:18.908
was perfect. I hadn't been here two weeks when the 
energy market collapsed Real estate went down the

02:22.220 --> 02:24.263
tubes. And he was kind enough not to hold me 
responsible. University life looked pretty

02:27.587 --> 02:29.109
good. University life looked better than ever. 
When was that? Was that about 83? Yeah, 83, 84. And

02:35.637 --> 02:36.598
it was interesting. His major concern was giving 
up tenure. He had this thing about tenure was

02:43.727 --> 02:48.413
probably a, what? He's got tremendous, 
tremendous respect. I think sometimes it borders

02:52.165 --> 02:55.489
on naivety about university life. I mean, I think 
he really does. The idea of somebody leaving the

02:59.294 --> 03:09.727
university, particularly with that tenure, and 
going into this risky, chancy, free market world.

03:10.969 --> 03:13.693
He was genuinely concerned about that. You know, I 
told him that was not something that he had to be

03:14.193 --> 03:18.619
concerned with, that that was a decision. that I 
could make. What he had to be concerned with was

03:20.192 --> 03:25.218
coming up with something that I would find 
attractive enough. And he did, and that was not a

03:25.238 --> 03:27.200
problem. So I've been here ever since as vice 
president for institutional development. It's a

03:35.110 --> 03:37.193
wonderful job. I mean, it's a reflection of 
Mitchell. Who else would hire a PhD in sociology?

03:42.980 --> 03:43.380
Who knows? Nothing about real estate knows 
nothing about energy. It's kind of interesting,

03:46.824 --> 03:48.927
because I have a lot of colleagues. and say, you 
know, I've been thinking seriously about getting

03:49.480 --> 03:53.525
into the private sector. How do you do that? And I 
said, listen, find another Mitchell. That's all I

03:57.731 --> 03:59.353
can tell you. So I continued to work with him on a 
variety of activities. How precisely, you

04:04.861 --> 04:11.229
mentioned that Holmes, was it President Holmes? 
Hoffman. Hoffman. Introduced you to George

04:14.193 --> 04:15.455
Mitchell. What was that initial, what did you do 
initially? Initially was to help him design,

04:19.400 --> 04:28.072
structure his first biannual conference on, it's 
called Limits to Growth. Oh. And that's when the

04:29.113 --> 04:42.291
Club of Rome was involved, and that first one, 
Dennis Meadows, who at Dartmouth had written

04:29.113 --> 04:42.291
several books on limits to growth and sustainable 
societies. There was a lot of interest in that

04:42.331 --> 04:47.618
topic. And George came up with some very, very nice 
prizes, five prizes of $10,000 each, and really

04:48.509 --> 05:04.055
put up a lot of money to do this for his conference. 
And then after the first conference on Limits to

05:05.677 --> 05:13.110
Growth, George realized that after all, he was 
calling for more and more energy exploration. He

05:13.671 --> 05:15.073
was a land developer. And he really didn't believe 
that we had reached the limits to growth. But he was

05:19.497 --> 05:24.042
much more comfortable with the notion of 
sustainable society. And he's got a tremendous

05:24.282 --> 05:29.468
commitment to protecting the environment, the 
ecology. You don't just have to look around here.

05:31.711 --> 05:33.312
The guy is very, very reluctant. I mean, there's 
many, many opportunities for him to sell land at a

05:33.332 --> 05:39.319
very great profit. He won't simply because of the 
needs or putting buildings, commercial

05:43.117 --> 05:49.664
buildings, and giving up frontage and so on. So I 
was involved with that. Then he had this great

05:50.905 --> 05:59.233
vision and the need for economic diversification 
for Houston and Texas. And he became very much

06:00.114 --> 06:10.204
aware that there were a lot of exciting and viable 
inventions and discoveries coming out of Texas,

06:00.114 --> 06:10.204
particularly out of the universities. But much of 
it was going elsewhere because there was no

06:10.859 --> 06:14.663
venture capital here. The only thing the banks 
were interested in was investing in oil. He once

06:20.069 --> 06:26.435
told a story of some guy walks into a bank and says, I 
have a cure for cancer. And they say, we can't do

06:26.495 --> 06:28.297
anything for you. And the other guy walks in and 
says, I have a black box. He says, what's in there?

06:31.200 --> 06:32.422
He says, a new way of getting oil. He says, here's a 
million dollars.

06:37.268 --> 06:43.656
He then formed the Woodlands Venture Capital 
Company and put up five million dollars. Hired a

06:43.676 --> 06:46.279
guy to really start. Fifteen's over there. Oh, 
fifteen's over there. It's five and then five and

06:48.903 --> 06:50.865
then five. It's a total of fifteen. Hired Marty 
Sutter, who came in to run Woodlands Venture

06:52.207 --> 06:56.812
Capital. And just about the same time, We started 
to think of this consortium of Texas universities

06:59.223 --> 07:19.504
that could come together at the Woodlands and 
really work on big-ticket items, complement one

06:59.223 --> 07:19.504
another, and create a major basic research center 
that would have spin-offs for

06:59.223 --> 07:19.504
commercialization. And you got involved in that 
early on? Right, right, yeah. I was asked, I

07:23.548 --> 07:27.492
chaired the feasibility committee. At that time, 
UT was not involved. A&M

07:30.667 --> 07:36.376
was involved, U of H, and Rice. And they had very 
good people on the committee, all of whom decided

07:38.340 --> 07:48.457
that they were so busy that they couldn't devote 
the time to this that was really necessary. So we

07:48.977 --> 07:50.560
went out and we got A.D. to do the feasibility 
study, and that was a self-fulfilling prophecy.

07:55.157 --> 08:00.363
They got $50,000 to find out it was a viable idea, 
and they said, yeah, this is a really viable idea.

08:00.383 --> 08:04.649
And they came up with a master plan, and most of the 
plan was disregarded anyway. But it was like, this

08:05.270 --> 08:09.736
now has been blessed. At the same time, George 
decided, geez, while I'm doing this over here, I

08:09.756 --> 08:17.526
really ought to do something, and I'll just do this 
on the medical side. So he went to A.D. Little again

08:18.400 --> 08:21.825
and said, take a look at the medical. And his dream 
there was that something like Hark, but a

08:21.865 --> 08:28.293
collection of the medical research. Do you see 
both of these things as having really emanated

08:29.996 --> 08:33.621
from George Mitchell per se? Yeah. Where was the 
input? No, it was him. It's him. The whole

08:38.367 --> 08:43.714
superconductor, supercollider, again, never 
would have happened without Mitchell. I mean, the

08:43.734 --> 08:47.800
guys at A&M, like Russ Houston and Peter McIntyre, 
no question about it. played a very significant

08:48.202 --> 08:49.703
role. But if George hadn't been there at the 
beginning and said, here's a facility, I'll put up

08:49.723 --> 09:06.499
money, here's housing for the scientists, I'll do 
this matching part, because I remember Russ Youth

08:49.723 --> 09:06.499
and I went to Chicago and signed that first 
contract with DOE, or the first magnet. Oh, did

09:06.519 --> 09:07.100
you? Okay. And George had to make some serious 
commitments before. There was nothing here.

09:13.306 --> 09:15.508
Yeah, so... Yeah, that's, those things I know. I 
know that Hark and the medical, the research

09:19.809 --> 09:27.320
center, medically, never would have happened. 
